Leave-One-Out Brier Score for survival models

Using Pareto smoothed importance sampling

Eren M. ElÃ§i

2018-11-21

In this document we show how to implement a leave-one-out version of the so-called âinverse of probability of censoring weighted estimatorâ (below referred to as Brier Score) for time dependent prediction accuracy of Bayesian survival models.

We use Pareto-Smoothed importance sampling here in order to avoid re-running the Bayesian analysis for any leave-one-out instance.

We provide an efficient implementation written in Stan and exposed to R.

log_lik_1 <- extract_log_lik(fit, merge_chains = FALSE)
r_eff <- relative_eff(exp(log_lik_1)) 
loo_1 <- loo(log_lik_1, r_eff = r_eff, cores = 2)
print(loo_1)

Brier Score (LOO-PSIS)

\[ S_i(t\vert \mathbf{T}_{-i}) \approx \frac{\sum_{s=1}^S r_{s,i} S_i(t\vert \theta_s)}{\sum_{s=1}^S r_{s,i}} \]

with

\[ r_{s,i} \equiv \frac{1}{p(T_i\vert \theta_s)} \]

\[ \eta_{i,t} \equiv \left\{ 1_{\{T_i > t\}} - S_i(t\vert \mathbf{T}_{-i})\right\}^2 \]

Based on the residuals \(\eta_{i,t}\) using the pec R Package, we calculate the so-called inverse of probability of censoring weighted estimator (below referred to as Brier Score)
